<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n56105l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56105l">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56105l"> 105(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the virgin <font face="wake">D</font>b</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The corncrake, a strenuous bard, discourses; the lofty <mark>virgin</mark> waterfall sings a welcome to to the warm pool; the talk of the rushes is come. <small> Tom Peete Cross and Clark Harris Slover, <a name="AIT1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AIT1"><cite title="source">Ancient Irish Tales</cite></a>  ([Nov. 1936]) 266</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In late August 1938, in conversation with Jacques Mercanton, Joyce said: &ldquo;In Shaun&apos;s sermon I use a term I heard an Englishman in Zurich use to designate the wine-waitress. He called her &lsquo;the virgin.&rsquo; Why not?&rdquo; Diligent searching has failed to reveal this unit in the relevant part (III.2) of the Wake. Joyce may not actually have used it; he may have simply intended to use it (see Willard Potts, ed. <cite>Portraits of the Artist in Exile</cite> (Dublin, 1979) p.224. </mm> </dd></dl>
